    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-05-08T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-05-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="1133"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1133">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.6363/54.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">British Ambassador</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">British Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-05-08">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 8, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: I have sent to Sir Lionel Garden
                    the telegram from our Consul at Tampico, a paraphrase of which I handed to you
                    yesterday; and have added that as the oil wells in that district are close
                    together, and the British companies owning some of them employ United States
                    citizens, it would be quite impossible to draw any distinction of British or
                    American nationality between either wells or employees: and that all sympathy
                    would be alienated both here and elsewhere if these properties were
                    destroyed.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cecil Spring Rice</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
